ard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2355<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/28/02 8:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Robotic Orion Starship.</span><hr size=1> In discussions about harnessing the Sun's fusion furnace on a flyby to gain acceleration I was thinking what a waste it is that the ship would be limited to only a few G's gain. Anymore would turn crew into jello unless they were a very hardy lot. Like Honda robots perhaps. What is the acceleration safety level of circuits? We might be able to construct a sail big enough to collect much more photon kinetic energy. We have to grab as much free power as possible while close to the sun. One of the bonuses being that when falling toward the sun for the flyby we can take along as much reaction mass as we like. The ship will still fall at the same rate. We can use up half of it departing the sun and the other half for breaking in reverse fashion at the destination star. Thats before even taking years of 'laser push' into account.<br>
<br>
Ofcourse, even if a computer controlled mission to A Centaurii were possible in 5 short years, it would need to be prepared for the completely unforeseeable. Quite impossible ofcourse. Therefore we would have to prepare it for everything we possibly could. A relay of 10 years in communications could be too lengthy for dire situations needing immediate solutions.<br>
<br>
One thing I would recommend is strategically placed nukes throughout the ship. Anything breaks in and can't be contained or reasoned with, the whole ship goes. Every useful piece of technology sent back to its component particles. We couldn't afford to risk possibly hostile enemies learning of our strengths and weaknesses. Atleast we would have a laser transmission of everything that had happened up to the point of catastrophe though. Even if we did get it 5 years late. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A> at: 10/28/02 8:09:34 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 128<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/28/02 8:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Robotic Orion Starship.</span><hr size=1> Good idea, except for the self destruct feature. Any aliens that would want to invade us would be able to push us aside without any effort, with or without knowing our weaknesses. From that it is safe to conclude that it would be a waste of space. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1302<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/29/02 1:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Robotic Orion Starship.</span><hr size=1> And laser communication with the home world would only pinpoint Earth's location for the 'Aliens'...<br>
<br>
This sounds like the Man/K'Zin War novels... anyone here ever read a book from that series? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 74<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/29/02 2:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Robotic Orion Starship.</span><hr size=1> Radio waves sent out over the past century would have already pinpointed our location to anyone close enough to recieve them. Let's hope old 1930's radio westerns, or even better TV episodes of the Three Stooges, don't start an interplanetary war. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2364<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/7/02 7:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Robotic Orion Starship.</span><hr size=1> You guys are assuming too much. Aliens are unlikely to be very similar to us. The wide variety of life forms down here is testament to that. Their brains will be completely unfathomable. Their sciences will be shaped by their evolution. You can't simply extrapolate human civilisation one million years into the future. It doesn't work like that. Some animals haven't changed one iota in hundreds of millions of years. Most are rather selective in mental ability. Even the smartest ones. Dolphins have no interest or clear conception of construction yet a tiny brained bird can build ornate nests. Aliens might have developed space travel but no understanding of nuclear power whatsoever. We can't guess at what they might know. Giving them a starship filled with &quot;Alien&quot; technology for them to poke at would be a grave error. The universal library contains infinite books on every possible reality, technology and event but visitors only travel down the aisles they are familiar with. We could be telling them about whole new wings they never considered before. Invention is the combination of different ideas. Take two separate sources of knowledge and make something new. That's how revolutionary technologies appear. <br>
Now I admit that the chances of life existing at Proxima Centaurii seem quite slim. After all it is a common double star system and any habitable planet might not have been stable for long. We can't ignore the possibility though. Like an asteroid impact, there is a small but existing chance and the consequences could be devastating if it is ignored. <br>
China invented bamboo one shot bang sticks and let the technology spread to the west. The west then later arrived with repeater rifles and took over. Alpha Centaurii might have been colonised by visitors from an older system. Just as we are talking of doing the same. Alerting them to our existance would be bad enough when we know nothing of them. Giving them the measure of us and quite possibly knowledge they don't already posess could be very bad. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 146<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/7/02 7:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Robotic Orion Starship.</span><hr size=1> The laws of physics are the same everywhere. Even if they are ignorant of U, Pu, &amp; Th, they would suspect them and be well aware of fission and fusion. Also, they would probably have developed power sources far greater than atoms, like anti-matter.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 344<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/7/02 8:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Robotic Orion Starship.</span><hr size=1> I think any society that produces great amounts of anti-matter would probably have discovered radioactive elements and their uses.  A society that produces copious amounts of anti-matter would need a powerful source of energy to do that.  Solar might be feasible if they had a planet like Mercury where the sun is right on your doorstep, but something like nuclear fusion would be a more likely method of producing the energy necessary for anti-matter production.   <br>
<br>
  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1385<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/7/02 8:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Alien form</span><hr size=1> The human form is built for intelligence... consider:<br>
<br>
Bipedal locomotion, freeing the hands (with opposable thumbs) to <br>
carry objects and manipulate the surroundings unimpeded, stimulating <br>
brain activity.<br>
<br>
Binocular vision allowing three dimensional perception.<br>
<br>
Vocal system allowing for a wide range of sounds to be produced, allowing<br>
for the development of a complex language.<br>
<br>
