I have long supported the Aquatic Ape theory. This answers questions I have pondered all my life. We learned to walk as a way of crossing water in north east Africa after catastrophic environmental changes brought floods to the region. Transforming it to an Amazon like terrain. Not for tool use. That came later. Food was short so we supplemented our diets with shellfish. Even otters and crows know how to smash a shell with a rock. This bvecame the first tool. Spears were developed from pointy sticks as a way of catching unwary fish. Our streamlined design, subcutaneous fat and sound communication are evolved from adaptations to semi-aquatic existance. We are the only mammal to have become fully upright walking as a consequence. The Proboscis monkey of the Amazon is one of only two monkeys in the World that can swim and it has been observed to 'walk' across deeper crossings.<br>
I say we are the only mammal to have aquired an upright posture due to semi-aquatic living but not the only animal. A semi-aquatic bird has also achieved a straight spine with head centred. The penguin. We are the result of environmental changes and that is why we can control our breathing and have a diving reflex while other primates fear water. They generally keep far away from it and get moisture from fruit. We on the other hand are slaves to natural water sources. We have far more sweat glands than our closest kin. Thats evolutionary madness for a land animal which doesn't dwell very near or in water. It's quite common for animals to return atleast partially to a watery existance. Elephants and pigs are also believed to have been semi-aquatic and still love swimming. The Hippo still is largely aquatic. Crocodiles have remained semi-aquatic for hundreds of millions of years. Others made a total transition, such as the doglike ancestors of Dolphins and Whales. There are water snakes, rats, spiders countless other species.<br>
